Carl Linneus came up with a formal way to classify living things.  By 1753 it was organized enough for academic adoption and is still largely in place today.

This is a bit curious.  Acrostics as a wordplay have existed since antiquity, but they weren't developed as puzzles untul 1935, several decades after Pirates of Penzance was produced.  The Major General says he "answers hard acrostics," implying that he's working on a puzzle of some kind, but he couldn't possible be, nor could Gilbert and Sullivan have known what an acrostic puzzle was.
